Description: Body sherd of Corinthian black-figured pottery open vessel, probably a kylix; interior: glazed (only slight traces remaining); exterior: black-figure decoration consisting of bird (breast, tail and legs remaining) to left; below, worn glazed area, probably bands.
Curator's comments: Venit identifies the sherd as an aryballos, but since it was glazed on its interior it must be an open vessel (Venit 1982, 68, no. A55).
Bibliographic references: Möller 2000 / Naukratis, Trade in Archaic Greece (p. 221, no. 4)
Venit 1982 / Painted Pottery from the Greek Mainland found in Egypt, 640-450 BC (p. 68, no. A55)
Villing et al 2013-2015 / Naukratis: Greeks in Egypt (GB.094) (Phase 1)
